instructions = 'This week\'s contest answer words are the first and last names of three famous people, as indicated in the grid. One person\'s first and last names total eleven letters, the second person\'s total twelve letters, and the third person\'s total thirteen letters.'
explanation = '<MA>JACQUES BARZUN, FELIX POTVIN, and DWIGHT YOAKAM</MA><TEXT>As indicated by 52-Across, the three names clued by the first three theme answers collectively contain every letter of the alphabet.<br/><br/> Remarkably, Matt only needed three names totalling 36 letters to accomplish this. After revealing the solution Matt challenged readers to come up with a pangrammatic set of names whose letters total fewer than 36. His record stood for over 4 years until being beaten by Peter Gordon in mid-2013. Gordon\'s 35-letter set of DIEGO VELAZQUEZ, FOXY BROWN, and JACK THOMPSON was voted legitimate by MGWCC solvers.<br/><br/>Using a massive list of names from Wikipedia and a PERL script, Alex Boisvert soon after made a reasonable case for 35 being the lower limit, in my opinion. Read more <a href="http://alexboisvert.com/musings/2013/07/09/pangram-names/" target="_blank">here</a>. Of course, new names are becoming famous all the time, and since the stage name FOXY BROWN was deemed legitimate then the record could be broken if some rising star were to pick a stage name with just the right combination of rare letters.<br/><br/>Lastly, in case you were wondering, Matt implemented the current difficulty scale (puzzles and metas get harder throughout the month) the week this puzzle was released. Since it was the last Friday of the month, he made this one quite difficult.</TEXT>'
